# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: convex-hull-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] In computational geometry, **Chan's algorithm**, named after Timothy M.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] Chan, is an optimal output-sensitive algorithm to compute the convex hull of a set P of n points, in 2- or 3-dimensional space.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] The algorithm takes $O(n\log h)$ time, where h is the number of vertices of the output (the convex hull).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] In the planar case, the algorithm combines an $O(n\log n)$ algorithm (Graham scan, for example) with Jarvis march ( $O(nh)$ ), in order to obtain an optimal $O(n\log h)$ time.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] Chan's algorithm is notable because it is much simpler than the Kirkpatrick–Seidel algorithm, and it naturally extends to 3-dimensional space.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] This paradigm has been independently developed by Frank Nielsen in his Ph.D. thesis.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] A single pass of the algorithm requires a parameter m which is between 0 and n (number of points of our set P ).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] Ideally, $m=h$ but h , the number of vertices in the output convex hull, is not known at the start.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] Multiple passes with increasing values of m are done which then terminates when $m\geq h$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] The algorithm starts by arbitrarily partitioning the set of points P into $K=\lceil n/m\rceil$ subsets $(Q_{k})_{k=1,2,...K}$ with at most m points each; notice that $K=O(n/m)$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] For each subset $Q_{k}$ , it computes the convex hull, $C_{k}$ , using an $O(p\log p)$ algorithm (for example, Graham scan), where p is the number of points in the subset.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] As there are K subsets of $O(m)$ points each, this phase takes $K\cdot O(m\log m)=O(n\log m)$ time.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] During the second phase, Jarvis's march is executed, making use of the precomputed (mini) convex hulls, $(C_{k})_{k=1,2,...K}$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] The convex hull of the set $Q_{k}$ , $C_{k}$ , is known and contains at most m points (listed in a clockwise or counter-clockwise order), which allows to compute $f(p_{i},Q_{k})$ in $O(\log m)$ time by binary search.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] Hence, the computation of $f(p_{i},Q_{k})$ for all the K subsets can be done in $O(K\log m)$ time.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] Then, we can determine $f(p_{i},P)$ using the same technique as normally used in Jarvis's march, but only considering the points $(f(p_{i},Q_{k}))_{1\leq k\leq K}$ (i.e. the points in the mini convex hulls) instead of the whole set P .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] For those points, one iteration of Jarvis's march is $O(K)$ which is negligible compared to the computation for all subsets.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] By running the two phases described above, the convex hull of n points is computed in $O(n\log h)$ time.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] If an arbitrary value is chosen for m , it may happen that $m<h$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] In that case, after m steps in the second phase, we interrupt the Jarvis's march as running it to the end would take too much time.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] At that moment, $O(n\log m)$ time will have been spent, and the convex hull will not have been calculated.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] The idea is to make multiple passes of the algorithm with increasing values of m ; each pass terminates (successfully or unsuccessfully) in $O(n\log m)$ time.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] If m increases too slowly between passes, the number of iterations may be large; on the other hand, if it rises too quickly, the first m for which the algorithm terminates successfully may be much larger than h , and produce a complexity $O(n\log m)>O(n\log h)$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] One possible strategy is to *square* the value of m at each iteration, up to a maximum value of n (corresponding to a partition in singleton sets).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] Starting from a value of 2, at iteration t , $m=\min \left(n,2^{2^{t}}\right)$ is chosen.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] To generalize this construction for the 3-dimensional case, an $O(n\log n)$ algorithm to compute the 3-dimensional convex hull by Preparata and Hong should be used instead of Graham scan, and a 3-dimensional version of Jarvis's march needs to be used.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] The time complexity remains $O(n\log h)$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] In the following pseudocode, text between parentheses and in italic are comments.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] To fully understand the following pseudocode, it is recommended that the reader is already familiar with Graham scan and Jarvis march algorithms to compute the convex hull, C , of a set of points, P .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/chan-s-algorithm] A "squaring scheme" is used as described above in this article.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Algorithms that construct convex hulls of various objects have a broad range of applications in mathematics and computer science.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] In computational geometry, numerous algorithms are proposed for computing the convex hull of a finite set of points, with various computational complexities.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Computing the convex hull means that a non-ambiguous and efficient representation of the required convex shape is constructed.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] The complexity of the corresponding algorithms is usually estimated in terms of *n*, the number of input points, and sometimes also in terms of *h*, the number of points on the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Consider the general case when the input to the algorithm is a finite unordered set of points on a Cartesian plane.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] An important special case, in which the points are given in the order of traversal of a simple polygon's boundary, is described later in a separate subsection.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] If not all points are on the same line, then their convex hull is a convex polygon whose vertices are some of the points in the input set.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Its most common representation is the list of its vertices ordered along its boundary clockwise or counterclockwise.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] In some applications it is convenient to represent a convex polygon as an intersection of a set of half-planes.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] For a finite set of points in the plane, the lower bound on the computational complexity of finding the convex hull represented as a convex polygon is easily shown to be the same as for sorting using the following reduction.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Since they lie on a parabola, which is a convex curve, it is easy to see that the vertices of the convex hull, when traversed along the boundary, produce the sorted order of the numbers $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Clearly, linear time is required for the described transformation of numbers into points and then extracting their sorted order.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Therefore, in the general case the convex hull of n points cannot be computed more quickly than sorting.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] The standard $\Omega (n\log n)$ lower bound for sorting is proven in the decision tree model of computing, in which only numerical comparisons but not arithmetic operations can be performed; however, in this model, convex hulls cannot be computed at all.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Sorting also requires $\Omega (n\log n)$ time in the algebraic decision tree model of computation, a model that is more suitable for convex hulls, and in this model convex hulls also require $\Omega (n\log n)$ time.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] As stated above, the complexity of finding a convex hull as a function of the input size n is lower bounded by $\Omega (n\log n)$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] However, the complexity of some convex hull algorithms can be characterized in terms of both input size n and the output size h (the number of points in the hull).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Such algorithms are called output-sensitive algorithms.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] They may be asymptotically more efficient than $\Theta (n\log n)$ algorithms in cases when $h=o(n)$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] The lower bound on worst-case running time of output-sensitive convex hull algorithms was established to be $\Omega (n\log h)$ in the planar case.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] There are several algorithms which attain this optimal time complexity.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] The earliest one was introduced by Kirkpatrick and Seidel in 1986 (who called it "the ultimate convex hull algorithm").
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] A much simpler algorithm was developed by Chan in 1996, and is called Chan's algorithm.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Known convex hull algorithms are listed below, ordered by the date of first publication.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Time complexity of each algorithm is stated in terms of the number of inputs points n and the number of points on the hull h .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Note that in the worst case h may be as large as n .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] The following simple heuristic is often used as the first step in implementations of convex hull algorithms to improve their performance.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] It is based on the efficient convex hull algorithm by Selim Akl and G.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] The idea is to quickly exclude many points that would not be part of the convex hull anyway.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] This method is based on the following idea.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Find the two points with the lowest and highest x-coordinates, and the two points with the lowest and highest y-coordinates.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] (Each of these operations takes O(*n*).) These four points form a convex quadrilateral, and all points that lie in this quadrilateral (except for the four initially chosen vertices) are not part of the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Finding all of these points that lie in this quadrilateral is also O(*n*), and thus, the entire operation is O(*n*).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Optionally, the points with smallest and largest sums of x- and y-coordinates as well as those with smallest and largest differences of x- and y-coordinates can also be added to the quadrilateral, thus forming an irregular convex octagon, whose insides can be safely discarded.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] The discussion above considers the case when all input points are known in advance.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Insertion of a point may increase the number of vertices of a convex hull at most by 1, while deletion may convert an *n*-vertex convex hull into an *n-1*-vertex one.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] The online version may be handled with O(log *n*) per point, which is asymptotically optimal.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] The dynamic version may be handled with O(log2 *n*) per operation.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] The convex hull of a simple polygon is divided by the polygon into pieces, one of which is the polygon itself and the rest are *pockets* bounded by a piece of the polygon boundary and a single hull edge.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Although many algorithms have been published for the problem of constructing the convex hull of a simple polygon, nearly half of them are incorrect.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] McCallum and Avis provided the first correct algorithm.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] A later simplification by Graham & Yao (1983) and Lee (1983) uses only a single stack data structure.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Their algorithm traverses the polygon clockwise, starting from its leftmost vertex.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] As it does, it stores a convex sequence of vertices on the stack, the ones that have not yet been identified as being within pockets.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] At each step, the algorithm follows a path along the polygon from the stack top to the next vertex that is not in one of the two pockets adjacent to the stack top.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Then, while the top two vertices on the stack together with this new vertex are not in convex position, it pops the stack, before finally pushing the new vertex onto the stack.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] When the clockwise traversal reaches the starting point, the algorithm returns the sequence of stack vertices as the hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] A number of algorithms are known for the three-dimensional case, as well as for arbitrary dimensions.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Chan's algorithm is used for dimensions 2 and 3, and Quickhull is used for computation of the convex hull in higher dimensions.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] For a finite set of points, the convex hull is a convex polyhedron in three dimensions, or in general a convex polytope for any number of dimensions, whose vertices are some of the points in the input set.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] Its representation is not so simple as in the planar case, however.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull-algorithms] In higher dimensions, even if the vertices of a convex polytope are known, construction of its faces is a non-trivial task, as is the dual problem of constructing the vertices given the faces.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In geometry, the **convex hull**, **convex envelope** or **convex closure** of a shape is the smallest convex set that contains it.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The convex hull may be defined either as the intersection of all convex sets containing a given subset of a Euclidean space, or equivalently as the set of all convex combinations of points in the subset.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For a bounded subset of the plane, the convex hull may be visualized as the shape enclosed by a rubber band stretched around the subset.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Convex hulls of open sets are open, and convex hulls of compact sets are compact.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Every compact convex set is the convex hull of its extreme points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The convex hull operator is an example of a closure operator, and every antimatroid can be represented by applying this closure operator to finite sets of points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The algorithmic problems of finding the convex hull of a finite set of points in the plane or other low-dimensional Euclidean spaces, and its dual problem of intersecting half-spaces, are fundamental problems of computational geometry.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] They can be solved in time $O(n\log n)$ for two or three dimensional point sets, and in time matching the worst-case output complexity given by the upper bound theorem in higher dimensions.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] As well as for finite point sets, convex hulls have also been studied for simple polygons, Brownian motion, space curves, and epigraphs of functions.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Convex hulls have wide applications in mathematics, statistics, combinatorial optimization, economics, geometric modeling, and ethology.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Related structures include the orthogonal convex hull, convex layers, Delaunay triangulation and Voronoi diagram, and convex skull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] A set of points in a Euclidean space is defined to be convex if it contains the line segments connecting each pair of its points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For bounded sets in the Euclidean plane, not all on one line, the boundary of the convex hull is the simple closed curve with minimum perimeter containing X .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] One may imagine stretching a rubber band so that it surrounds the entire set S and then releasing it, allowing it to contract; when it becomes taut, it encloses the convex hull of S .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] This formulation does not immediately generalize to higher dimensions: for a finite set of points in three-dimensional space, a neighborhood of a spanning tree of the points encloses them with arbitrarily small surface area, smaller than the surface area of the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] However, in higher dimensions, variants of the obstacle problem of finding a minimum-energy surface above a given shape can have the convex hull as their solution.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For objects in three dimensions, the first definition states that the convex hull is the smallest possible convex bounding volume of the objects.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] It is not obvious that the first definition makes sense: why should there exist a unique minimal convex set containing X , for every X ?
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] However, the second definition, the intersection of all convex sets containing X , is well-defined.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] It is a subset of every other convex set Y that contains X , because Y is included among the sets being intersected.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Thus, it is exactly the unique minimal convex set containing X .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Therefore, the first two definitions are equivalent.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Each convex set containing X must (by the assumption that it is convex) contain all convex combinations of points in X , so the set of all convex combinations is contained in the intersection of all convex sets containing X .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Conversely, the set of all convex combinations is itself a convex set containing X , so it also contains the intersection of all convex sets containing X , and therefore the second and third definitions are equivalent.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In fact, according to Carathéodory's theorem, if X is a subset of a d -dimensional Euclidean space, every convex combination of finitely many points from X is also a convex combination of at most $d+1$ points in X .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The set of convex combinations of a $(d+1)$ -tuple of points is a simplex; in the plane it is a triangle and in three-dimensional space it is a tetrahedron.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Therefore, every convex combination of points of X belongs to a simplex whose vertices belong to X , and the third and fourth definitions are equivalent.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In two dimensions, the convex hull is sometimes partitioned into two parts, the upper hull and the lower hull, stretching between the leftmost and rightmost points of the hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] More generally, for convex hulls in any dimension, one can partition the boundary of the hull into upward-facing points (points for which an upward ray is disjoint from the hull), downward-facing points, and extreme points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For three-dimensional hulls, the upward-facing and downward-facing parts of the boundary form topological disks.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The *closed convex hull* of a set is the closure of the convex hull, and the *open convex hull* is the interior (or in some sources the relative interior) of the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The closed convex hull of X is the intersection of all closed half-spaces containing X .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] If the convex hull of X is already a closed set itself (as happens, for instance, if X is a finite set or more generally a compact set), then it equals the closed convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] However, an intersection of closed half-spaces is itself closed, so when a convex hull is not closed it cannot be represented in this way.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] If the open convex hull of a set X is d -dimensional, then every point of the hull belongs to an open convex hull of at most $2d$ points of X .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The sets of vertices of a square, regular octahedron, or higher-dimensional cross-polytope provide examples where exactly $2d$ points are needed.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Topologically, the convex hull of an open set is always itself open, and (in Euclidean spaces) the convex hull of a compact set is always itself compact.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] However, there exist closed sets for which the convex hull is not closed.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] (the set of points that lie on or above the witch of Agnesi) has the open upper half-plane as its convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Convex hulls can be defined more generally in infinite-dimensional topological vector spaces, but they may not preserve compactness in these spaces.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Instead, the compactness of convex hulls of compact sets, in finite-dimensional Euclidean spaces, is generalized by the Krein–Smulian theorem, according to which the closed convex hull of a weakly compact subset of a Banach space (a subset that is compact under the weak topology) is weakly compact.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] An extreme point of a convex set is a point in the set that does not lie on any open line segment between any other two points of the same set.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For a convex hull, every extreme point must be part of the given set, because otherwise it cannot be formed as a convex combination of given points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] According to the Krein–Milman theorem, every compact convex set in a Euclidean space (or more generally in a locally convex topological vector space) is the convex hull of its extreme points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] However, this may not be true for convex sets that are not compact; for instance, the whole Euclidean plane and the open unit ball are both convex, but neither one has any extreme points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Choquet theory extends this theory from finite convex combinations of extreme points to infinite combinations (integrals) in more general spaces.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] When applied to a finite set of points, this is the closure operator of an antimatroid, the shelling antimatroid of the point set.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Every antimatroid can be represented in this way by convex hulls of points in a Euclidean space of high-enough dimension.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The operations of constructing the convex hull and taking the Minkowski sum commute with each other, in the sense that the Minkowski sum of convex hulls of sets gives the same result as the convex hull of the Minkowski sum of the same sets.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] This provides a step towards the Shapley–Folkman theorem bounding the distance of a Minkowski sum from its convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The projective dual operation to constructing the convex hull of a set of points is constructing the intersection of a family of closed halfspaces that all contain the origin (or any other designated point).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The convex hull of a finite point set $S\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ forms a convex polygon when $d=2$ , or more generally a convex polytope in $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Each extreme point of the hull is called a vertex, and (by the Krein–Milman theorem) every convex polytope is the convex hull of its vertices.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] It is the unique convex polytope whose vertices belong to S and that encloses all of S .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For sets of points in general position, the convex hull is a simplicial polytope.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] According to the upper bound theorem, the number of faces of the convex hull of n points in d -dimensional Euclidean space is $O(n^{\lfloor d/2\rfloor })$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In particular, in two and three dimensions the number of faces is at most linear in n .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The convex hull of a simple polygon encloses the given polygon and is partitioned by it into regions, one of which is the polygon itself.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The other regions, bounded by a polygonal chain of the polygon and a single convex hull edge, are called *pockets*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Computing the same decomposition recursively for each pocket forms a hierarchical description of a given polygon called its *convex differences tree*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Reflecting a pocket across its convex hull edge expands the given simple polygon into a polygon with the same perimeter and larger area, and the Erdős–Nagy theorem states that this expansion process eventually terminates.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The curve generated by Brownian motion in the plane, at any fixed time, has probability 1 of having a convex hull whose boundary forms a continuously differentiable curve.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] However, for any angle $\theta$ in the range $\pi /2<\theta <\pi$ , there will be times during the Brownian motion where the moving particle touches the boundary of the convex hull at a point of angle $\theta$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The Hausdorff dimension of this set of exceptional times is (with high probability) $1-\pi /2\theta$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For the convex hull of a space curve or finite set of space curves in general position in three-dimensional space, the parts of the boundary away from the curves are developable and ruled surfaces.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The convex hull or lower convex envelope of a function f on a real vector space is the function whose epigraph is the lower convex hull of the epigraph of f .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] It is the unique maximal convex function majorized by f .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The definition can be extended to the convex hull of a set of functions (obtained from the convex hull of the union of their epigraphs, or equivalently from their pointwise minimum) and, in this form, is dual to the convex conjugate operation.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In computational geometry, a number of algorithms are known for computing the convex hull for a finite set of points and for other geometric objects.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Computing the convex hull means constructing an unambiguous, efficient representation of the required convex shape.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Output representations that have been considered for convex hulls of point sets include a list of linear inequalities describing the facets of the hull, an undirected graph of facets and their adjacencies, or the full face lattice of the hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In two dimensions, it may suffice more simply to list the points that are vertices, in their cyclic order around the hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For convex hulls in two or three dimensions, the complexity of the corresponding algorithms is usually estimated in terms of n , the number of input points, and h , the number of points on the convex hull, which may be significantly smaller than n .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For higher-dimensional hulls, the number of faces of other dimensions may also come into the analysis.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Graham scan can compute the convex hull of n points in the plane in time $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For points in two and three dimensions, more complicated output-sensitive algorithms are known that compute the convex hull in time $O(n\log h)$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] These include Chan's algorithm and the Kirkpatrick–Seidel algorithm.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] For dimensions $d>3$ , the time for computing the convex hull is $O(n^{\lfloor d/2\rfloor })$ , matching the worst-case output complexity of the problem.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The convex hull of a simple polygon in the plane can be constructed in linear time.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Dynamic convex hull data structures can be used to keep track of the convex hull of a set of points undergoing insertions and deletions of points, and kinetic convex hull structures can keep track of the convex hull for points moving continuously.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The construction of convex hulls also serves as a tool, a building block for a number of other computational-geometric algorithms such as the rotating calipers method for computing the width and diameter of a point set.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Several other shapes can be defined from a set of points in a similar way to the convex hull, as the minimal superset with some property, the intersection of all shapes containing the points from a given family of shapes, or the union of all combinations of points for a certain type of combination.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Each of alpha shape is the union of some of the features of the Delaunay triangulation, selected by comparing their circumradius to the parameter alpha.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The point set itself forms one endpoint of this family of shapes, and its convex hull forms the other endpoint.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The convex layers of a point set are a nested family of convex polygons, the outermost of which is the convex hull, with the inner layers constructed recursively from the points that are not vertices of the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The convex skull of a polygon is the largest convex polygon contained inside it.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] It can be found in polynomial time, but the exponent of the algorithm is high.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Convex hulls have wide applications in many fields.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Within mathematics, convex hulls are used to study polynomials, matrix eigenvalues, and unitary elements, and several theorems in discrete geometry involve convex hulls.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] They are used in robust statistics as the outermost contour of Tukey depth, are part of the bagplot visualization of two-dimensional data, and define risk sets of randomized decision rules.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Convex hulls of indicator vectors of solutions to combinatorial problems are central to combinatorial optimization and polyhedral combinatorics.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In economics, convex hulls can be used to apply methods of convexity in economics to non-convex markets.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In geometric modeling, the convex hull property Bézier curves helps find their crossings, and convex hulls are part of the measurement of boat hulls.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] And in the study of animal behavior, convex hulls are used in a standard definition of the home range.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Newton polygons of univariate polynomials and Newton polytopes of multivariate polynomials are convex hulls of points derived from the exponents of the terms in the polynomial, and can be used to analyze the asymptotic behavior of the polynomial and the valuations of its roots.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Convex hulls and polynomials also come together in the Gauss–Lucas theorem, according to which the roots of the derivative of a polynomial all lie within the convex hull of the roots of the polynomial.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In spectral analysis, the numerical range of a normal matrix is the convex hull of its eigenvalues.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The Russo–Dye theorem describes the convex hulls of unitary elements in a C*-algebra.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In discrete geometry, both Radon's theorem and Tverberg's theorem concern the existence of partitions of point sets into subsets with intersecting convex hulls.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The definitions of a convex set as containing line segments between its points, and of a convex hull as the intersection of all convex supersets, apply to hyperbolic spaces as well as to Euclidean spaces.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] However, in hyperbolic space, it is also possible to consider the convex hulls of sets of ideal points, points that do not belong to the hyperbolic space itself but lie on the boundary of a model of that space.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The boundaries of convex hulls of ideal points of three-dimensional hyperbolic space are analogous to ruled surfaces in Euclidean space, and their metric properties play an important role in the geometrization conjecture in low-dimensional topology.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Hyperbolic convex hulls have also been used as part of the calculation of canonical triangulations of hyperbolic manifolds, and applied to determine the equivalence of knots.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] See also the section on Brownian motion for the application of convex hulls to this subject, and the section on space curves for their application to the theory of developable surfaces.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In robust statistics, the convex hull provides one of the key components of a bagplot, a method for visualizing the spread of two-dimensional sample points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The contours of Tukey depth form a nested family of convex sets, with the convex hull outermost, and the bagplot also displays another polygon from this nested family, the contour of 50% depth.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In statistical decision theory, the risk set of a randomized decision rule is the convex hull of the risk points of its underlying deterministic decision rules.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In combinatorial optimization and polyhedral combinatorics, central objects of study are the convex hulls of indicator vectors of solutions to a combinatorial problem.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] If the facets of these polytopes can be found, describing the polytopes as intersections of halfspaces, then algorithms based on linear programming can be used to find optimal solutions.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In multi-objective optimization, a different type of convex hull is also used, the convex hull of the weight vectors of solutions.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] One can maximize any quasiconvex combination of weights by finding and checking each convex hull vertex, often more efficiently than checking all possible solutions.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In the Arrow–Debreu model of general economic equilibrium, agents are assumed to have convex budget sets and convex preferences.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] These assumptions of convexity in economics can be used to prove the existence of an equilibrium.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] When actual economic data is non-convex, it can be made convex by taking convex hulls.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The Shapley–Folkman theorem can be used to show that, for large markets, this approximation is accurate, and leads to a "quasi-equilibrium" for the original non-convex market.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In geometric modeling, one of the key properties of a Bézier curve is that it lies within the convex hull of its control points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] This so-called "convex hull property" can be used, for instance, in quickly detecting intersections of these curves.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In the geometry of boat and ship design, chain girth is a measurement of the size of a sailing vessel, defined using the convex hull of a cross-section of the hull of the vessel.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] It differs from the skin girth, the perimeter of the cross-section itself, except for boats and ships that have a convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The convex hull is commonly known as the minimum convex polygon in ethology, the study of animal behavior, where it is a classic, though perhaps simplistic, approach in estimating an animal's home range based on points where the animal has been observed.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In quantum physics, the state space of any quantum system — the set of all ways the system can be prepared — is a convex hull whose extreme points are positive-semidefinite operators known as pure states and whose interior points are called mixed states.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The Schrödinger–HJW theorem proves that any mixed state can in fact be written as a convex combination of pure states in multiple ways.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] A convex hull in thermodynamics was identified by Josiah Willard Gibbs (1873), although the paper was published before the convex hull was so named.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] In a set of energies of several stoichiometries of a material, only those measurements on the lower convex hull will be stable.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] When removing a point from the hull and then calculating its distance to the hull, its distance to the new hull represents the degree of stability of the phase.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The lower convex hull of points in the plane appears, in the form of a Newton polygon, in a letter from Isaac Newton to Henry Oldenburg in 1676.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] The term "convex hull" itself appears as early as the work of Garrett Birkhoff (1935), and the corresponding term in German appears earlier, for instance in Hans Rademacher's review of Kőnig (1922).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/convex-hull] Other terms, such as "convex envelope", were also used in this time frame.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] In computational geometry, the **gift wrapping algorithm** is an algorithm for computing the convex hull of a given set of points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] In the two-dimensional case the algorithm is also known as **Jarvis march**, after R.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] Jarvis, who published it in 1973; it has O(*nh*) time complexity, where *n* is the number of points and *h* is the number of points on the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] Its real-life performance compared with other convex hull algorithms is favorable when n is small or h is expected to be very small with respect to n.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] In general cases, the algorithm is outperformed by many others (see Convex hull algorithms).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] For the sake of simplicity, the description below assumes that the points are in general position, i.e., no three points are collinear.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] The algorithm may be easily modified to deal with collinearity, including the choice whether it should report only extreme points (vertices of the convex hull) or all points that lie on the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] Also, the complete implementation must choose how to deal with degenerate cases when the convex hull has only 1 or 2 vertices, as well as with the issues of limited arithmetic precision, both of computer computations and input data.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] The gift wrapping algorithm begins with *i*=0 and a point *p0* known to be on the convex hull, e.g., the leftmost point, and selects the point *pi+1* such that all points are to the right of the line *pi pi+1*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] This point may be found in *O*(*n*) time by comparing polar angles of all points with respect to point *pi* taken for the center of polar coordinates.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] Letting *i*=*i*+1, and repeating with until one reaches *ph*=*p0* again yields the convex hull in *h* steps.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] In two dimensions, the gift wrapping algorithm is similar to the process of winding a string (or wrapping paper) around the set of points.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] The approach can be extended to higher dimensions.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] The inner loop checks every point in the set *S*, and the outer loop repeats for each point on the hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] The run time depends on the size of the output, so Jarvis's march is an output-sensitive algorithm.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] However, because the running time depends linearly on the number of hull vertices, it is only faster than $O(n\log n)$ algorithms such as Graham scan when the number *h* of hull vertices is smaller than log *n*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/gift-wrapping-algorithm] Chan's algorithm, another convex hull algorithm, combines the logarithmic dependence of Graham scan with the output sensitivity of the gift wrapping algorithm, achieving an asymptotic running time $O(n\log h)$ that improves on both Graham scan and gift wrapping.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] The first step in this algorithm is to find the point with the lowest y-coordinate.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] If the lowest y-coordinate exists in more than one point in the set, the point with the lowest x-coordinate out of the candidates should be chosen.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] This step takes O(*n*), where *n* is the number of points in question.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] Next, the set of points must be sorted in increasing order of the angle they and the point *P* make with the x-axis.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] Any general-purpose sorting algorithm is appropriate for this, for example heapsort (which is O(*n* log *n*)).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] Sorting in order of angle does not require computing the angle.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] It is possible to use any function of the angle which is monotonic in the interval $[0,\pi ]$ .
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] The cosine is easily computed using the dot product, or the slope of the line may be used.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] If numeric precision is at stake, the comparison function used by the sorting algorithm can use the sign of the cross product to determine relative angles.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] If several points are of the same angle, either break ties by increasing distance (Manhattan or Chebyshev distance may be used instead of Euclidean for easier computation, since the points lie on the same ray), or delete all but the furthest point.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] The algorithm proceeds by considering each of the points in the sorted array in sequence.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] For each point, it is first determined whether traveling from the two points immediately preceding this point constitutes making a left turn or a right turn.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] If a right turn, the second-to-last point is not part of the convex hull, and lies 'inside' it.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] Again, determining whether three points constitute a "left turn" or a "right turn" does not require computing the actual angle between the two line segments, and can actually be achieved with simple arithmetic only.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] If the result is 0, the points are collinear; if it is positive, the three points constitute a "left turn" or counter-clockwise orientation, otherwise a "right turn" or clockwise orientation (for counter-clockwise numbered points).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] This process will eventually return to the point at which it started, at which point the algorithm is completed and the stack now contains the points on the convex hull in counterclockwise order.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] Sorting the points has time complexity O(*n* log *n*).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] While it may seem that the time complexity of the loop is O(*n*2), because for each point it goes back to check if any of the previous points make a "right turn", it is actually O(*n*), because each point is considered at most twice in some sense.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] Each point can appear only once as a point $(x_{2},y_{2})$ in a "left turn" (because the algorithm advances to the next point $(x_{3},y_{3})$ after that), and as a point $(x_{2},y_{2})$ in a "right turn" (because the point $(x_{2},y_{2})$ is removed).
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] The overall time complexity is therefore O(*n* log *n*), since the time to sort dominates the time to actually compute the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] The pseudocode below uses a function ccw: ccw > 0 if three points make a counter-clockwise turn, ccw < 0 if clockwise, and ccw = 0 if collinear.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] Then let the result be stored in the `stack`.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] Now the stack contains the convex hull, where the points are oriented counter-clockwise and P0 is the first point.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] Here, `next_to_top()` is a function for returning the item one entry below the top of stack, without changing the stack, and similarly, `top()` for returning the topmost element.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/graham-scan] This pseudocode is adapted from *Introduction to Algorithms*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] N-dimensional Quickhull was invented in 1996 by C.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] It was an extension of Jonathan Scott Greenfield's 1990 planar Quickhull algorithm, although the 1996 authors did not know of his methods.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Instead, Barber et al. describe it as a deterministic variant of Clarkson and Shor's 1989 algorithm.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Use the line formed by the two points to divide the set into two subsets of points, which will be processed recursively.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] We next describe how to determine the part of the hull above the line; the part of the hull below the line can be determined similarly.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Determine the point above the line with the maximum distance from the line.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] This point forms a triangle with the two points on the line.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] The points lying inside of that triangle cannot be part of the convex hull and can therefore be ignored in the next steps.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Recursively repeat the previous two steps on the two lines formed by the two new sides of the triangle.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Continue until no more points are left, the recursion has come to an end and the points selected constitute the convex hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] The problem is more complex in the higher-dimensional case, as the hull is built from many facets; the data structure needs to account for that and record the line/plane/hyperplane (ridge) shared by neighboring facets too.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] For each *F* in *Fs[]*, find all unassigned points that are "above" it; i.e., pointing away from the center of the hull, and assign them to an "outside" set *F.O* associated with *F*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] The algorithm maintains the invariant that every point that has not been added to the hull but could potentially be a vertex of it is assigned to exactly one outside set.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Create a visible set *V* and initialize it to *F*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Extend *V* in all directions for neighboring facets *Fv* until no further facets are visible from *p*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] The boundary of *V* then forms the set of horizon ridges *H*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Let *Fnew[]* be the set of facets created from *p* and all ridges in *H*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Unassign all points in the outside sets of facets in *V.* For each new facet in *Fnew[]*, perform step (2) only considering these newly unassigned points to initialize its outside set.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Note that every point that remains unassigned at the end of this process lies within the current hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Delete the now-internal facets in *V* from *Fs[]*.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] Add the new facets in *Fnew[]* to *Fs[]* and continue the iteration.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] A pseudocode specialized for the 3D case is available from Jordan Smith.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] It includes a similar "maximum point" strategy for choosing the starting hull.
[src:convex-hull-algorithms/quickhull] If these maximum points are degenerate, the whole point cloud is as well.
